    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "can u explain the math behind it a bit more? like how specifically is the interest calculated each month and why does it feel like it's eating up most of my money before it even touches the principal?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The math is simple: each month, the bank first calculates interest based on the remaining balance and the loan's annual rate, dividing that annual rate by 12 for a monthly figure. Since your balance is highest at the start of the loan, the interest charge is also at its peak, meaning a large chunk of your fixed payment is spent just to cover that cost. Once that interest is paid, whatever is left goes to the principal, so when the interest bill is huge, your principal reduction looks negligible. As the balance shrinks, the interest charge gets smaller, allowing your entire payment to start digging into the principal much sooner.",
      "source": "target",
